Sychronous, Multi-processing, Multi-threading, Async.excalidraw

Sychronous, Multi-processing, Multi-threading, Async.excalidraw

Created:  Nov 15, 2023
Modified: Nov 15, 2023
8265 words, 42 min read

  • #excalidraw

⚠ Switch to EXCALIDRAW VIEW in the MORE OPTIONS menu of this document. ⚠

Text Elements §

Threads are less resource heavy than process ^qnV0NHFK

Frequent Access to Shared Data

Single Core, CPU Bounded

Single Core, IO/Network Bounded

Multi Core, CPU Bounded

Multi Core, IO/Network Bounded

Async Synchronous

Multi-processing & Multi-threading will just result in context switching overhead

Multi-threading Async

Multi-processing context switching too ex

Synchronous is is blocking, waiting time is all wasted

Async Multi-threading

Async should be slighly faster, since only one thread to create, and not context switching overhead(ignorable)

no

Async

We need mutex to prevent race condition, and risk of deadlock for multi-threading

yes

Multi-processing Multi-threading

Async & Synchronous are single threaded, cant take advantage of Multi Core

Frequent Access to Shared Data

Conclusion: 1)Async works well when there is single core, in both CPU & IO/Bounded tasks 2) Multi-processing cant make it

Muti-threading

no

Multi-processing

yes

For multi-threading, Race conditions & deadlocks are complex to program with Overhead incurred from mutex

Multi-threading Multi-processing Async

Want high concurrency

Multi-threading Multi-processing Async

No

Synchronous means one thread that is blocking So we can only carry out the next task when we finish waiting

Frequent Access to Shared Data

Multi-threading Multi-processing Async

No

Multi-processing Async

Yes

For multi-threading, Race conditions & deadlocks are complex to program with Overhead incurred from mutex

Multi-processing Async

Multi-processing requires more resources to create And context switching is exprensive if we want more processes than the number of CPU cores

Yes

Frequent Access to Shared Data

Multi-threading Async

No

Async

Yes

For multi-threading, Race conditions & deadlocks are complex to program with Overhead incurred from mutex

Conclusion:

  1. Async doesn’t work well when there is multi core, CPU bounded tasks

  2. Async works well when there is multi core, IO/Network bounded tasks, the un-used cores can be used for CPU bounded tasks like encryption

  3. Multi-processing shines when no high concurrency is needed
